article.description: Hakim Warrick had 19 points, 10 rebounds and five assists to lead No. 6 Syracuse to a 104-54 victory over Northern Colorado on Thursday night in the first round of the Coaches vs. Cancer Classic.
article.headline: Orange sophomore Roberts sprains knee in blowout
article.linkText: Warrick leads Syracuse rout of Northern Colorado
article.story: SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Syracuse had lost its last two season openers. The Orange weren't about to make it three in a row. Led by Hakim Warrick and Gerry McNamara, No. 6 Syracuse scored the first 24 points of the game and cruised to a 104-54 victory over Northern Colorado on Thursday night in the first round of the Coaches vs. Cancer Classic. Syracuse (1-0) will play Princeton (1-0) in the second round Friday night. The Tigers beat Bucknell 61-48 in the Carrier Dome earlier Thursday. "It's good to finally start off on the right track," said Warrick, a preseason All-America who had 19 points, 10 rebounds, five assists and four blocks. "Our defensive intensity got our offense going. We got a lot of easy shots." Northern Colorado, in only its second season back in Division I, had not played a ranked Division I team since 1957 and the Orange were merciless from the opening tip. Josh Pace started the rush with a jumper in the lane just 13 seconds in and McNamara fed Warrick for an alley-oop dunk to the get Orange off and running. Center Craig Forth converted a miss by Demetris Nichols, McNamara followed with two 3-pointers and Syracuse was up 12-0 after only 2:49. "That's how we wanted to come out. Any time you come out against a team and get on them early, that can devastate them," said McNamara, who had 11 points in an emotion-packed night for him. His father was in the stands for the first time since undergoing surgery. "You let a team hang around, they think they can play with us." The Bears (0-1) had no such illusions after that start. They missed their first eight shots and two free-throw attempts and committed five turnovers while Syracuse hit nine of its first 10 shots. Northern Colorado finally broke through on a 3-pointer by Sean Nolen at 12:27, but by then the game essentially was over. "Never in my wildest dreams did I think we would get ourselves down 24-zip," Northern Colorado coach Craig Rasmuson said. "We didn't even get a look at the basket. It was 9-0 before we put up our first shot." Pace had 13 points, Darryl Watkins had 12 and Nichols added 11 for Syracuse, which shot 67.3 percent in taking a 53-20 halftime lead. Sean Taibi had 16 points and seven rebounds and Nolen finished with eight points for the Bears, who shot 25.4 percent for the game. Forward Terrence Roberts, one of four sophomores Syracuse head coach Jim Boeheim is counting on this season, fell hard to the floor midway through the second half and hurt his left knee. He lay writhing in pain for more than a minute before being helped to the locker room. After the game Roberts said he was OK and expected to play against Princeton, an opponent that concerned Boeheim. "You can't really prepare for Princeton because nobody can execute like they do," Boeheim said. "They're a very difficult team to play."
